Principle of Conservation of Angular Momentum

If the net external torque on an -particle system is zero, then the system's total angular momentum is constant. That is,
The validity of this principle depends on the assumption that all internal forces are central (lie on the line joining two particles) and satisfy the third law (which does not hold in relativity). Notably, the gravitational force between two particles is central, which makes this property especially useful.

Angular Momentum about the Center of Mass

The conservation of angular momentum and the general result was derived with the assumption that both and were measured about an origin fixed in some inertial frame. This was necessary so the second law could be used. The same result also holds if and are measured about the center of mass (which is not a fixed point). Remarkably, this holds even if the CM is being accelerated and so is not fixed in an inertial frame. So, if about the CM is , then about the CM is conserved.
